[[File:D%C3%A9fil%C3%A92007.jpg|right|thumb|upright=1.1|300px|Carnival parade in [[Cayenne]]]]
'''[[Carnival]] in [[French Guiana]]''' is a major event. Its style is described as [[Afro-Caribbean]].{{sfn|Brown|Read|2003|p=57}} It was established in 1884 following the abolition of slavery.{{Sfn|Shafto|2009|p=57}} A moveable holiday, it takes place between [[Epiphany (holiday)|Epiphany]] and [[Ash Wednesday]], ending on [[Mardi Gras]].{{Sfn|West|2003|p=95}} The participants – French, Brazilian, Chinese and Creole people<ref name=kreolmagazine.com>{{cite news|title=Amazing Festivals The Carnival of French Guiana|url=http://www.kreolmagazine.com/music-entertainment/review-events/amazing-festivals-the-carnival-of-french-guiana/|accessdate=16 May 2015|publisher=Kreol International Magazine|date=6 May 2014}}</ref> – dress in vibrant costumes.{{Sfn|Cheng|2011|p=163}} Main events include a parade and a burlesque-style marriage. 

==Background==
This celebration is a cultural tradition of the [[Guianan Creole]], its origin traced to carnival customs practiced in Europe. It debuted during the beginning of colonization when settlers took part in carnival, forbidding the slaves from participating. Defying the ban, the slaves practiced carnival in clandestine ways, seeing it as a way to regain some freedom, to commemorate African fertility, and to deride the settlers. In the present day, metropolitan, Brazilian and Chinese communities take part in the event.<ref name=Hidair2011>{{cite web|last1=Hidair|first1=Isabelle|title=Le carnaval cayennais ou l'entretien symbolique de frontières "ethniques"|url=http://www.manioc.org/fichiers/V12099|publisher=CRILLASH : Centre de Recherches Interdisciplinaires en Lettres, Langues, Arts et Sciences Humaines|accessdate=16 May 2015|language=French|date=2011}}</ref> Its occurrence varies, prescribed by the religious calendar and taking place between the Epiphany in early January, and Ash Wednesday, which marks the beginning of [[Lent]]. Carnival ends on [[Shrovetide]].<ref name=imagesplus.fr>{{cite web|title=
Carnaval de Guyane|url=http://www.imagesplus.fr/CARNAVAL-DE-GUYANE_a24.html|website=imagesplus.fr|accessdate=16 May 2015|language=French}}</ref>

==Traditional costumes==
{{multiple image
  |direction = vertical
  |align     = left
  |width     = 200
  |image1    = Touloulous.jpg
  |caption1  = ''[[Touloulou]]s''
  |image2    = Kourou neg marrons carnaval 2007 2.jpg
  |caption2  = ''Neg'Marrons''
}}
There are several traditional costumes in the French Guiana carnival, representing various figures. King Vaval is a mythical figure who serves as carnival king. He is introduced at the beginning of the festival and dies on Ash Wednesday, to be reborn like the Phoenix in the following year. The most famous character is the [[Touloulou]], an elegantly dressed lady who wears a petticoat, hood, [[Domino mask]], and long gloves, so that none of her skin is visible. The aim of the woman who masquerades as a ''touloulou'' is to not be recognized. She strolls down the street and participates in the masked balls. The character represents the bourgeois women of 18th and 19th centuries. Neg'Marrons are groups of men dressed in ''kalimbé'' (red [[loincloth]]) and coated with [[molasses]].<ref name=kreolmagazine.com /> Representing fugitive slaves, they seek to make order of the festival. Other traditional characters include the ''Zombi baréyo'', a [[zombie]] character; ''Jwé farin'', who is dressed in white trousers, shirt, pointed hat, and mask, representing a baker; ''Bobi'', is dressed in old potato sacks and appears as a bear led by a leash; ''Karolin'', representing a rich woman with gold who is jealous and protects other women; ''Lanmò'', who represents death, is dressed in white; '' Soussouris'', who represents the bat, is a winged character who commonly wears black or two tones, and is renowned for its vampire behavior; and ''Diab rouj'' (red devil), who dresses in red and black.<ref name=imagesplus.fr /> The ''tululu'' (mask) is worn in French Guiana while celebrating carnival.{{sfn|Fauquenoy|1972|p=50}}

==Food and drink== 
{{multiple image
  |direction = vertical
  |align     = right
  |width     = 200
  |image1    = Galette des Rois.png
  |caption1  = ''Galette des rois''
  |image2    = Kourou carnaval dragon chinois 2007.jpg
  |caption2  = Carnival dragon
}}
Fridays commonly include eating a cake, known as the ''[[galette des rois]]'' (cake of kings, which in mainland France would be eaten only for the [[Epiphany (holiday)|Epiphany]]),<ref name=kreolmagazine.com /> representing the [[Three Kings]].{{sfn|Albala|2011|p=144}} [[Blaff]] is also commonly consumed during this period.{{sfn|Albala|2011|p=144}}

==Events== 
On the Saturday preceding Lent, carnival Queens (locally, ''Touloulous'') dress in colourful, camouflaged dresses and wear masks while they dance through the streets. Their costumes – lace and petticoats, tights and gloves – cover them from head to toe. They speak in disguised voices to retain anonymity.{{Sfn|Shafto|2009|p=57}} The women invite the men to join them, which is a mandatory requirement.{{Sfn|Gray|1999|p=279}} On Friday and Saturday nights, the Toulouois assemble in large dance halls. Men who are invited have to pay an entry fee.{{Sfn|Shafto|2009|p=57}} Sunday is the day of parades.{{Sfn|Gray|1999|p=279}} ''Vides'' (street parades), require months of preparation.{{sfn|Horn|Laing|2005|p=320}} They occur on the streets of [[Cayenne]], [[Kourou]], and [[Saint-Laurent-du-Maroni]]. Groups dress according to the theme of the year. The parade includes decorated floats and there are musicians playing drums and brass. Thousands of spectators line the sidewalks and sit in the stands which are set up for the occasion. Brazilian groups have similar costumes to those encountered at [[Rio Carnival]], while the country's Asian community incorporates dragons in the festivities. On Monday, a sham act of marriage with women (brides) in men's gowns and men (grooms) in women's dresses is the main spectacle.{{Sfn|Gray|1999|p=279}} Tuesday, the last day of the festival, is marked by the appearance of the main spirit of King Vaval, who is considered by the locals to be "the devil and soul of carnival". He arrives on a canoe in the form of an effigy, made of straw. A very large number of people gather on the beach to welcome him.{{Sfn|Shafto|2009|p=57}}{{Sfn|Gray|1999|p=279}} On this occasion the dancers are dressed in black or red coloured costumes adorned with horns and tails and holding pitchforks. The effigy is then burnt in the night and on the following day, Ash Wednesday, people wear black and white dresses to mourn the passing of Vival.{{Sfn|Gray|1999|p=279}}

