{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = Love and Responsibility | title_orig = [[:pl:Miłość i odpowiedzialność|Miłość i Odpowiedzialność]] | translator = H. T. Willetts | image = Love and Responsibility.jpg | caption = Cover to the English first edition | author = [[Pope John Paul II|Karol Wojtyła]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = Roxanne Mei Lum | country = Poland | language = Polish | series = | subject = [[Love]] and [[Human sexuality|Human Sexuality]] | genre = | publisher = [[William Collins (publisher)|William Collins Sons & Co. Ltd.]], [[London]] and [[Farrar, Straus and Giroux|Farrar, Straus and Giroux, Inc.]], [[New York City]] | pub_date =1960 | english_pub_date =1981 | release_date = 1960 | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover|Hardback]] & [[Paperback]]) & Audio book | pages = 319 | isbn = 0-89870-445-6 | dewey= 241/.66 20 | congress= BT708 .J6313 1993 | oclc = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Love and Responsibility''''' is a book written by Karol Wojtyła before he became [[Pope John Paul II]] and was originally published in [[Polish language|Polish]] in 1960 and in English in 1981.<ref name="Wojtyła">[[#Wojtyła69|Wojtyła, Karol. ''Love and Responsibility'']]: 1981</ref><ref name="Catholic">{{cite web |url=http://www.catholic.org/featured/headline.php?ID=321 |title=How not to be used: Love and Responsibility – Catholic Online |publisher=www.catholic.org |accessdate=2009-10-11 }}</ref><ref name="Summary">{{cite web |url=http://www.christendom-awake.org/pages/may/summaryofl&r.htm |title=A Summary of Karol Wojtyła's Love and Responsibility by William E. May |publisher=www.christendom-awake.org |accessdate=2009-10-14 }}</ref> A new, completely updated and original translation was published in 2013.<ref>Translated by Grzegorz Ignatik, published by Pauline Books & Media, Boston, MA.</ref>
The work consists of five chapters; "The Person and the Sexual Urge"; "The Person and Love"; "The Person and Chastity"; "Justice to the Creator"; and "Sexology and Ethics".<ref name="Summary"/> It is described as 'a defence of the traditional Church teachings on marriage from a new philosophical standpoint'.<ref name="Kuhiwczak">{{cite web|url=http://www.polskieradio.pl/zagranica/news/artykul21561.html|title=A literary Pope|last=Kuhiwczak|first=Piotr (Dr.)|date=1 January 2007|work=Polish Radio |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080208070732/http://www.polskieradio.pl/ |archivedate=February 8, 2008 |publisher= 2007,2009 Nowe Media, Polskie Radio S.A.|accessdate=2009-01-01}}</ref> In his introduction to the first edition, Fr. Wojtyla describes his reasons for writing the book as being "born principally of the need to put the norms of Catholic sexual morality on a firm basis, a basis as definitive as possible, relying on the most elementary and incontrovertible moral truths and the most fundamental values or goods".<ref>{{cite book|last=Wojtyla|first=Karol|title=Love and Responsibility|year=1981|publisher=Ignatius Press|location=San Francisco|isbn=978-0-89870-445-7|pages=16}}</ref> Fr. Wojtyła was originally inspired to write the book while being a professor at the [[John Paul II Catholic University of Lublin|Catholic University of Lublin]],<ref name="pp2bio">{{cite book | author = Weigel, George |title = Witness of Hope – The Biography of Pope John Paul II | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 2001}}</ref> through the experiences he had in teaching young Catholics.
While at the university, Fr. Wojtyła gathered a group of about 20 young people, who began to call themselves ''‘Rodzinka’'', the "little family". They met for prayers, [[philosophy|philosophical]] discussions, and helping the blind and sick. The group eventually grew to approximately 200 participants, and their activities expanded to include annual [[skiing]] and [[kayak]]ing trips.<ref name="USCCB_Bio">{{cite web |url=http://www.usccb.org/about/leadership/holy-see/pope-john-paul-ii/pope-john-paul-ii-biography.cfm |title=Pope John Paul II: A Light for the World |accessdate=2011-10-23| publisher=United States Council of Catholic Bishops |year=2003}}</ref> The insight he gained from these meetings and discussions helped him develop the raw material for the text.
[[Pope John Paul II|Fr. Wojtyła]] writes that marital [[sexual intercourse]] is the best image of God who is love, for he sees the human body as the only one capable of making the invisible — the spiritual and the divine — visible.<ref name="Wojtyła"/><ref>Karol Woytyla, Love and Responsibility, San Francisco, [[Ignatius Press]] 1993</ref><ref name="Edward">{{cite web |url=http://www.holyspiritinteractive.net/columns/edwardpsri/loveandresponsibility/02.asp|title=Holy Spirit Interactive: Edward P. Sri – Love and Responsibility: The Battle for Purity |publisher=www.holyspiritinteractive.net|accessdate=2009-10-15}}</ref> He says that human beings were created by God for a purpose: to be persons who freely choose to love, to give themselves as persons who express their self-giving through their bodies. Thus, sexual intercourse between [[Marriage|husband and wife]] is a [[symbol]] of their total mutual self-donation, and further fosters, strengthens and enriches it not just for the present but also for the future.<ref name="Wojtyła"/><ref name="Edward"/> For Fr. Wojtyła, "The body, and it alone, is capable of making visible what is invisible: the spiritual and divine."<ref name="Wojtyła"/><ref>Theology of Marriage and Celibacy, Boston, St. Paul Books and Media 1986</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://catholiceducation.org/articles/sexuality/se0109.html|author=Christopher West|work=Catholic Education Resource Centre|title=What is the Theology of the Body & Why is it Changing so Many Lives?|accessdate=2009-09-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.columbia.edu/cu/augustine/arch/jp2/love-resp.html |title=Love and Responsibility: The Person and Love |publisher=www.columbia.edu |accessdate=2009-10-15 }}</ref> {{cquote|Marriage is an act of will that signifies and involves a mutual gift, which unites the spouses and binds them to their eventual souls, with whom they make up a sole family – a domestic church.|25px|25px|<small>[[Pope John Paul II|Karol Wojtyła]] </small><ref name="Quotes2">{{cite web |url=http://www.brainyquote.com/quotes/authors/p/pope_john_paul_ii.html|title=BrainyQuote: ''Pope John Paul II Quotes''|accessdate=2009-10-15|publisher=[[copyright|]] 2007,2009 BrainyMedia.com}}</ref>}}
