{{other uses}}
[[File:Milarepa-statue-made-by-root-student-rechungpa.jpg|thumb|238px|A famous statue of Milarepa brought from Nyanang Phelgyeling Monastery, Tibet]]
{{Tibetan Buddhism}}
'''Jetsun Milarepa''' ({{bo|t=རྗེ་བཙུན་མི་ལ་རས་པ|w=rje btsun mi la ras pa}}, 1028/40–1111/23){{sfn|Quintman|p=536}} was a Tibetan [[siddha]], who famously was a murderer as a young man then turned to Buddhism to become an accomplished buddha despite his past. He is generally considered as one of [[Tibet]]'s most famous [[yogi]]s and poets, serving as an example for the Buddhist life. He was a student of [[Marpa Lotsawa]], and a major figure in the history of the [[Kagyu]] school of [[Tibetan Buddhism]].{{sfn|Quintman|p=536}}

==Biography==

===''The Life of Milarepa''===
[[File:Gompa at Milarepa's cave.JPG|thumb|Overlooking Pelgyeling Gompa at [[Milarepa's Cave]], Tibet.]]
[[File:Sekhar Gutog monastery in Lhodrag near Bhutan.jpg|thumb|The nine storey tower that Milarepa single-handedly built, Sekhar Gutok, Lhodrag, Tibet.]]

Milarepa's life-story is famous in the Tibetan culture, and retold many times. The best-known biography, ''The Life of Milarepa'', written by [[Tsangnyön Heruka]] (1452-1507) in the fifteenth century and drawing from older biographies, is still very popular.{{sfn|Quintman|2004|p=536}}{{sfn|Lopez|2010}}{{sfn|Quintman|2010}} Most of the present-day stories on Milarepa come from this single source.{{sfn|Quintman|2010}} While "very little [is known] about him as a historical person at all," Milarepa is venerated by all Tibetan schools "as an exemplar of religious dedication and mastery," and his lifestory established the lineage of the Kagyu sect and its key figures.{{sfn|Quintman|2010}}

According to ''The Life of Milarepa'', Milarepa was born in western Tibet to a prosperous family.{{sfn|Quintman|p=536}} When his father died, his family was bereft of their wealth by his aunt and uncle. At his mother's request, Milarepa left home and studied [[Magic (supernatural)|sorcery]] to take revenge, killing many people.{{sfn|Quintman|2004|p=536}} Later he felt sorrow about his deeds, and became student of [[Marpa Lotsawa|Marpa the Translator]]. Before Marpa would teach Milarepa, he had him undergo abuse and trials, such as letting him build and then demolish three towers in turn. Milarepa was asked to build one final multi-story tower by Marpa at Lhodrag, which still stands.<ref name="prm.ox.ac.uk">prm.ox.ac.uk: [http://tibet.prm.ox.ac.uk/photo_2001.59.4.50.1.html Sekhar Gutog monastery in Lhodrag near Bhutan]</ref> Eventually, Marpa accepted him, explaining that the trials were a means to purify Milarepa's negative karma.{{sfn|Quintman|2004|p=536}} Marpa transmitted tantric Tantric initiations and instructions to Milarepa, including ''[[tummo]]'' ("yogic heat"), the "aural transmissions" ({{bo|w=snyan rgyud}}), and ''[[mahamudra]]''.{{sfn|Quintman|2010}} Marpa told Milarepa to practice solitary meditation in caves and mountain retreats, which, according to the biography, after many years of practice resulted in "a deep experiential realization about the true nature of reality." Thereafter he lived as a fully realized yogin, and eventually even forgave his aunt, who caused the misfortune of his family.{{sfn|Quintman|2010}}

According to Lopez, ''The Life of Milarepa'' represents "Buddhism as it was understood and practiced in Tibet in the fifteenth century, projected back in time,"{{sfn|Lopez|2010}} and contains "many of the key terms and doctrines of Buddhism."{{sfn|Lopez|2010}} Tsangnyön Heruka did his best to establish a lineage of teachers which connects the Kagyu tradition with the Indian ''siddha'' tradition, portraying Marpa as a student of Naropa, though Naropa had already died when Marpa went to India.{{sfn|Lopez|2010}}

Lopez notes that Tsangnyön Heruka used stylistic elements from the biography of [[Gautama Buddha]] to portray Milarepa effectively as a Tibetan Buddha, "born and enlightened in Tibet, without going to India or receiving the direct instructions of an Indian master."{{sfn|Lopez|2010}} The lifestory of Milarepa portrays "the rapid method of the Tantric path,"in which liberation is gained in one lifetime. It describes how Milarepa practiced the generation stage and completion stage, to achieve ''[[mahamudra]]'', "spontaneous realization of the most profound [[Śūnyatā|nature of mind]]."{{sfn|Lopez|2010}} Yet, in his instructions to his Tibetan audiences, Milarepa refers to the basic Buddhist teachings of "impermanence, the sufferings of ''[[saṃsāra]]'', the certainty of death and the uncertainty of its arrival, the frightful rebirth that is the direct result of our benighted deeds." But, his own life also is an example that even a murderer can transform into a Buddha.{{sfn|Lopez|2010}} Lopez further notes that ''The Life of Milarepa'' portrays two parallel worlds, a profane world and a sacred world, which are ultimately one, showing that the world itself is sacred.{{sfn|Lopez|2010}}

===''The Hundred Thousand Songs of Milarepa''===
[[File:Milarepa,_Pango_Chorten,_Gyantse.JPG|thumb|Milarepa statue, Pango Chorten, [[Gyantse]], Tibet.]]

Previous biographies of Milarepa were enlarged with religious poetry and song cycles, which doubled the volume of biographical information.  Tsangnyön Heruka published these songs in a separate volume as ''The Hundred Thousand Songs of Milarepa'', summarizing the various song cycles in chapter eleven of ''The Life of Milarepa''.{{sfn|Quintman|2010}}

==Historical context==
Milarepa lived during the socalled [[Tibetan Buddhism#Tibetan Renaissance - second dissemination (10th-12th century)|second dissemination of Buddhism in Tibet]] (10th-12th century), when Buddhism was re-introduced. Three pivotal figures in this Tibetan Renaissance were [[Rinchen Zangpo]] (958-1055), who translated sutras, tantras and commentaries; [[Atiśa]] (982-1054), whose student [[Dromtön]] founded the [[Kadam (Tibetan Buddhism)|Kadam]] school of Tibetan Buddhism; and [[Marpa Lotsawa]], the teacher of Milarepa, and himself regarded as student of [[Naropa]]. Marpa introduced tantric texts and oral instructions from the Bengali [[siddha]] tradition into Tibet,{{sfn|Lopez|2010}} and Marpa's purported connection with Naropa established the lineage of the Kaguy school, thereby reaching back to the Buddha himself.{{sfn|Lopez|2010}}{{sfn|Quintman|2010}}

